[{"id":16607,"date":"2017-10-12T20:00:41","date_gmt":"2017-10-12T18:00:41","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/?post_type=contribution&#038;p=16607"},"modified":"2020-01-13T17:37:30","modified_gmt":"2020-01-13T16:37:30","slug":"anthropocene-lecture-julia-adeney-thomas","status":"publish","type":"contribution","link":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/contribution\/anthropocene-lecture-julia-adeney-thomas\/","title":{"rendered":"Anthropocene Lecture &#8211; Julia Adeney Thomas"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>The historians\u2019 task in the age of the Anthropocene: Finding hope in Japan?<\/p>\n<p> The historians\u2019 task in the age of the Anthropocene: Finding hope in Japan? <\/p>\n<p>Historians explore the past in order to understand not only our present but also our future trajectory. However, climate scientists today are now telling us that the conditions on our planet are changing so quickly and unpredictably that the past has no bearing on the future. If our challenges are unprecedented, is history reduced to mere antiquarianism? What are historians to do? This presentation explores this predicament and proposes a new form of critical history as we move from modernity\u2019s promise of freedom and development to the more modest goal of sustainability with decency, considering ways that an alternative history might be found by examining the economic, social, and political practices of early modern Japan.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The historians\u2019 task in the age of the Anthropocene: Finding hope in Japan? The historians\u2019 task in the age of the Anthropocene: Finding hope in Japan? Historians explore the past in order to understand not only our present but also our future trajectory. However, climate scientists today are now telling us that the conditions on [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":3,"template":"","method":[],"keyword":[210,222,226],"folksonomy":[],"acf":{"subtitle"